-- Hong Kong shares edge down on caution after China's rate cut
-- By Shanghai Newsroom
-- Tue Nov 25, 2014 03:04AM EST
-- None



Nov 25 (Reuters) - Hong Kong shares inched down on Tuesday as investors turned cautious and consolidated positions after gains spurred by China's surprise lending-rate cut.

The Hang Seng index <.HSI> dropped 0.2 percent, to 23,843.91 points. The Hong Kong China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> of top Chinese listings in Hong Kong lost 0.6 percent, to 10,782.91 points. Energy shares, including index components PetroChina <0857.HK> and Sinopec <0386.HK>, led losses as prices of U.S. crude and Brent fell ahead of an OPEC meeting this week.